Appendix 
This research is intended to be read by Ramesh Sangha, is a member of parliament representing Brampton Center, or his office. Attached is a research project which reports on findings between the representation of immigrants in Canadian identity through music. The document is laid out in 3 major sections. In the first section I dissect the messages and meaning behind some of the artists music, looking for calls to specific influences that they might have mentioned in their songs which would give me an indication as to what their experience might have been growing up in specific urban centers around the city. The second section analyzes the statistics of those regions, and substance abuse trends for the age groups that the artists would have associated with around the time of the rise in their popularity. Investigating the population sizes, first or second-generation immigrant populations, statistics on the use of marijuana and alcohol for those urban centers, and then combining the statistics to represent the relationship to immigrants. The final section includes pop culture references and looks to determine how the artists use their influence to promote multiculturalism as an identity in Canada. Initially it was very difficult to narrow down my selections of artists, as it meant filtering first those who were second-generation immigrants, and then listening to all of their music for themes referencing specific immigrant issues or experiences. Once I had discovered a theme, the next challenge was to research the history of the artists and all of their songs to determine how this theme related to their experience growing up in Toronto as a second-generation immigrant, and also what it meant to them to be from Toronto. The final challenge was to assemble the statistics required to support the theme described by the artists. Further research might try to determine why there is such a prominent party scene amongst youth in this country, and whether or not artist could be using their position to promote better alternatives to cope with the challenges of growing up and discovering an identity. 
